--- Johannes Link &lt;john.link@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; I guess you made the dialog modal. There&#39;s a flag
&gt; for that in the JDialog
&gt; constructor.
&gt; 
&gt; There are two approaches I have used in that
&gt; situation:
&gt; 1. Provide a constructor which opens the dialog in
&gt; non-modal mode just for
&gt; testing purposes.
&gt; 
&gt; 2. Open the dialog in another thread than the
&gt; testing thread:
&gt; private void openDialogInOtherThread() {
&gt;     Runnable runnable = new Runnable() {
&gt;         public void run() {
&gt;                 dialog.show(); // =
&gt; dialog.setVisible(true)
&gt;         }
&gt;     };
&gt;     new Thread(runnable).start();
&gt;     waitForDialogOpen();
&gt; }
&gt; private void waitForDialogOpen() {
&gt;     while (!dialog.isShowing()) {
&gt;         try {
&gt;             Thread.sleep(10);
&gt;         } catch (InterruptedException e) {
&gt;         }
&gt;     }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Now you can perform your tests on dialog as you
&gt; wish. Don&#39;t forget to call
&gt; dialog.dispose() in tearDown.
&gt; 
&gt; Hope that helps,
&gt; Johannes
&gt; 
